    <figcaption class="hero-text">
      <h1>Double VPN (Multi-hop): smart privacy for the US — or overkill?</h1>
      <p>What it is, when it helps, and how to configure it without killing your speeds.</p>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <!-- Quick answer + CTA (TOP) -->
  <div class="note">
    <p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> Double VPN (aka <em>multi-hop</em>) routes your traffic through two VPN servers instead of one. It improves IP separation and correlation resistance, but adds latency. In the US, it makes sense for: <br>
    — sensitive research, whistleblowing, doxxing protection; <br>
    — travel and work on untrusted networks (airports, hotels, campus); <br>
    — separating entry/exit jurisdictions. <br>
    <strong>Not ideal</strong> for streaming, gaming or everyday speed-heavy tasks — a fast single hop is better.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="cta">
    <a class="btn btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener noreferrer"
       href="https://go.nordvpn.net/aff_c?aff_id=2495&offer_id=312&url_id=2584">Try NordVPN — fast & stable</a>
    <br><small>Alternative: <a target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.tkqlhce.com/click-101525886-17061430">Surfshark</a></small>
  </p>

  <h2 id="what">What is Double VPN?</h2>
  <p>With a regular VPN, your device makes one encrypted tunnel to one server; that server forwards traffic to the internet. With Double VPN you create a chain: an encrypted tunnel to an <em>entry</em> server, and inside it a second tunnel to an <em>exit</em> server in a different location. The entry sees your real IP but not your destinations; the exit sees the destinations but not your real IP. That split makes timing and legal correlation harder.</p>

  <h2 id="how">How multi-hop works (plain English)</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Connect to server A (entry) with a modern protocol (WireGuard/NordLynx or OpenVPN).</li>
    <li>Inside that tunnel, your app dials server B (exit) and builds a second tunnel.</li>
    <li>Flow becomes: <code>Device → A (encrypt) → B (encrypt/decrypt) → Internet</code>; replies return the same path.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Because each hop knows only half of the story, a single observer has a tougher job linking “you” to “what site.” You still trust one provider, so it’s not Tor, but it’s a meaningful step up from single-hop for targeted-threat scenarios.</p>

  <h2 id="benefits">Real benefits for US users</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Jurisdiction split:</strong> Entry in one country, exit in another (e.g., Canada → US or US → Netherlands) complicates legal process and cross-border requests.</li>
    <li><strong>Extra IP separation:</strong> Sites only see the exit IP; your home or office IP never touches destination traffic.</li>
    <li><strong>Better against targeted harassment:</strong> Useful for journalists, OSINT researchers, union organizers, or anyone facing doxxing/swatting.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="tradeoffs">Trade-offs & limitations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Slower & higher latency:</strong> Two hops mean extra crypto and distance. Gamers and streamers should stick to single-hop.</li>
    <li><strong>Battery/CPU cost:</strong> Laptops and phones do more work; expect a hit on older hardware.</li>
    <li><strong>Not magic anonymity:</strong> Cookies, logins and fingerprinting still identify you. It’s stronger transport privacy, not a full cloak.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="when">When should Americans enable Double VPN?</h2>
  <p>Turn it on for high-risk travel, sensitive research, and publishing under a pseudonym. If you’re just banking, shopping, watching Netflix, or playing on Xbox/PS5, a nearby single-hop server with WireGuard is both safer <em>and</em> faster in practice.</p>

  <h2 id="config">Safe configuration tips (US)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Prefer WireGuard/NordLynx for the first hop; fall back to OpenVPN only on hostile networks. See <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-protocols.html">VPN protocols</a>.</li>
    <li>Enable a strict <strong>Kill Switch</strong> and block IPv6 leaks; run periodic checks. See <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-dns-leak.html">DNS leak basics</a>.</li>
    <li>Pick geographic pairs that make sense (e.g., New York → Chicago, Seattle → Vancouver, Miami → San Juan) instead of trans-oceanic chains.</li>
    <li>Avoid Double VPN for streaming libraries — single hop near the service wins. See <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-streaming.html">VPN for streaming</a>.</li>
    <li>Benchmark before keeping it on: <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-speed-test.html">VPN speed test</a>.</li>
    <li>If you need a stable, non-shared address for SaaS allowlists, use a <em>dedicated IP</em> on a single hop instead of multi-hop.</li>
    <li>Port-dependent apps? Multi-hop often disables forwarding. Details: <a href="/en-us/blog/vpn-port-forwarding.html">Port forwarding</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Practical US scenarios</h2>
  <p><strong>Conference Wi-Fi:</strong> You’re at DEF CON or RSA on a crowded network. Double VPN with an entry outside Nevada and an exit near your services adds friction for metadata correlation. <strong>Investigations:</strong> Researching sensitive topics from home? Multi-hop separates your ISP (Comcast, Spectrum, AT&amp;T, Cox) from the final destinations. <strong>Creator safety:</strong> If you get brigaded on social networks, double-hop helps decouple your home IP from your content workflow.</p>

  <!-- Video block -->
